<H3> <TI>   Secret Deals Prior to Plenary Session Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2502220594 Dakar PANA in English 1615 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2502220594 </F>
<F P=104>  Dakar PANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kinshasa, 25 Feb (PANA) -- Zairean President, Mobutu 
Sese Seko and his staunch opponent, Etienne Tshisekedi, whom he 
sacked as prime minister in late 1992, reportedly met Wednesday 
[23 February] night in Gbadolite, the birthplace of the former, 
Zairean papers revealed Friday. The alleged meeting took place 
a few days before the resuming of the plenary session of the 
transition parliament, due to open Saturday in Kinshasa to elect 
the prime minister. 
  The papers said the meeting between the two was the crowning 
of a series of secret deals which have been undertaken by a 
number of prominent Zaireans. Among those who involved in the 
secret conciliation efforts was the chairman of the Zairean 
National Union of Employers, Bemba Saolona, who is a close 
associate of President Mobutu. 
  Tshisekedi and his radical Union for Democracy and Social 
Progress (UPDS) have insisted that his sacking from the 
premiership was illegal because he was democratically elected by 
the 1991 national conference and not by the president. 

</TEXT>

