<H3> <TI>   Most Striking Peacekeepers Reportedly Back at Work </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0303163794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1556 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0303163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria March 3 SAPA -- The Transitional Executive 
Council [TEC] and members of its Sub-Council on Defence meet on 
Friday [4 March] in a bid to solve the pay grievances which 
sparked a strike by 3,100 members of the National Peacekeeping 
Force [NPKF]. NPKF spokesman Capt Johan Loots said on Thursday 
members of the TEC Management Council would visit the De Brug 
training camp, near Bloemfontein, on Monday to present the 
force's commander Maj-Gen Gabriel Ramushwana with a solution to 
the problem. 
  Capt Loots said the majority -- 98 per cent -- of the 
trainees who went on strike on Monday had returned to work, 
following a visit to the camp by TEC representatives. 

