<H3> <TI>   Portuguese Foreign Minister Meets With Mandela </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303161494 Lisbon RTP Internacional Television in 
Portuguese 1200 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0303161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RTP Internacional Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Italicized passages recorded] </F>
  [Excerpts] Foreign Minister Durao Barroso and Nelson 
Mandela have met in South Africa. Both came out in favor of 
peace and of a peaceful channeling of the South African 
electoral process. 
  [Correspondent Antonio Mateus] An election boycott poses a 
potential conflict situation in South Africa. After meeting the 
South African president, the ANC [African National Congress] 
president, and the PAC [Pan-Africanist Congress] president, 
Barroso still has reservations regarding the future of this 
country. The consensus between the government and the ANC raises 
hopes of a peaceful transition but this is not enough. Six 
weeks away from the elections the objective is to extend 
participation in the process. Barroso's message was echoed by 
some of those involved, anxious to prevent the worst. Barroso 
found today in Mandela an attentive listener to the Portuguese 
experience of transition in Africa. 
  [Mandela, in English with superimposed Portuguese 
translation] They have had a lot of experience regarding 
the problems that South Africa will have to face, because the 
former colonies, Angola and Mozambique, had difficult 
experiences that we do not want to see repeated in this country. 
I have found the exchange of opinion with him [Barroso] very 
useful in that regard. 
  [Mateus, interviewing Barroso on the street] After the 
brief contacts, are you more optimistic regarding the future of 
this country, or is it too early to say? 
  [Barroso] I still have many reservations because I think 
that 
until we can ensure that everyone will participate there will be 
the potential for destabilization. Essentially, I think there 
is a great consensus in South Africa -- for which it would be 
enough that the ANC and the National Party saw eye to eye -- but 
it is important for that agreement to be as widespread as 
possible in order to reduce to a minimum the potential for 
destabilization of some forces. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

