<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Parties Present Memorandum to Chissano </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0803073794 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
0400 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0803073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The unarmed opposition parties have accused the 
government of edging out and discriminating against political 
parties by not permitting their effective participation in the 
elections scheduled for October. In a memorandum submitted to 
the president of the republic, the opposition parties say under 
the prevailing conditions it is difficult for them to take part 
in the elections on an equal footing with the Mozambique 
Liberation Front and the Mozambique National Resistance 
[Renamo]. The memorandum says the government has no right to 
monopolize the State General Budget, alleging that the budget 
comes from tax payers, including members of the unarmed 
political parties. 
  The political parties rejected what they described as Renamo 
maneuvers designed to divide the country into two occupied 
areas. The parties demanded the immediate abolition of so-called 
Renamo areas and their rapid reintegration into state 
administration. 
  Speaking to newsmen after he received the memorandum, the 
president of the republic said he believed the unarmed 
opposition parties will not demand an immediate response to 
their grievances because these require an in-depth assessment of 
the situation. Joaquim Chissano said it is necessary for the 
country's leading forces to work closely. 
  Yesterday's meeting was requested by the unarmed political 
parties. 

</TEXT>

