<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, ANC on Bophuthatswana Election Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0703205494 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1900 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0703205494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government has warned Bophuthatswana that a new 
government will turn off the economic taps to the territory 
unless free political activity is allowed there. Foreign 
Affairs Minister Pik Botha appealed to moderates within the 
Bophuthatswana cabinet to reconsider a decision not to 
participate in the election. He expressed concern that the 
continuing strikes in the territory could spill over into South 
Africa and said the government would insist on free political 
activity in Bophuthatswana. 
  Mr. Popo Molefe of the ANC [African National Congress] said 
his party would insist that budget allocations to Bophuthatswana 
be halted. He said the ANC would also support the 
intensification of mass action in support of free political 
activity. 
  Meanwhile, reacting to the furor caused by his cabinet's 
decision, President Mangope has said that he is prepared to die 
for the independence of Bophuthatswana if necessary. He said 
neither the Transitional Electoral Council [as heard] nor the 
Independent Electoral Commission would be allowed to operate in 
Bophuthatswana unless the government decided to register for the 
election. 
  However, President Mangope expressed optimism that mediation 
could lead to agreement to parties before the election. 
[sentence as heard] He said it was now up to the Bophuthatswana 
parliament to decide whether the state would participate in the 
election. 

</TEXT>

