<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ANC Threatens To Cut Off Funds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0703204894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2026 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0703204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by C Molusi] </F>
  [Text] Johannesburg March 7 SAPA -- The African National 
Congress [ANC] will ensure budget allocation transfers to 
Bophuthatswana are halted to force the homeland government to 
allow canvassing for a free and fair election, ANC Election 
Commission head Popo Molefe said on Monday [7 March]. 
Addressing a media conference, Mr Molefe said the ANC would 
support the intensification of mass action in Bophuthatswana to 
ensure free political activity. "Bophuthatswana should be 
blockaded as a non-military step to force the homeland 
government to stop political persecution," he said. "The ANC 
election offices in the homeland were bombed on Monday as part 
of the campaign of harassment against the organisation including 
disruptions of voter education meetings." 
  Mr Molefe, the ANC premier nominee for the North Western 
Region which includes Bophuthatswana, called on State President 
F W de Klerk to act more firmly against the homeland and take 
away its powers. He suggested steps to force the homeland to 
allow political activity, including: 

  -  transitional executive council intervention; 
  -  the independent electoral commission erect polling booths in 
the area; 
  -  blockading the homeland to prevent entry of South African 
goods; 
  -  stopping the annual budget allocation to the homeland; and, 
  -  cutting financial loans to Bophuthatswana. 

    Mr Molefe said tourists should be discouraged from going to 
the homeland, although he admitted the move would hurt the 
economy and lead to a loss of jobs, but added it was more 
important to stop tyranny. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

