<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   After Delay, Transitional Government Sworn In </TI></H3>
<H4>   Swearing-In Detailed </H4>
<F P=102> AB0703184394 London BBC World Service in English 1705 GMT 7 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0703184394 </F>
<F P=104>  London BBC World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Focus on Africa" program] </F>
  [Text] It has been a day of political confusion in Liberia 
today, where the Transitional Council was due to be sworn in 
this morning. Last week, the leadership of ULIMO [United 
Liberation Movement for Democracy in Liberia] which signed the 
Cotonou Peace Accord with the NPFL [National Patriotic Front of 
Liberia] and the interim government, was split by a challenge to 
Alhaji Koromah. Today's swearing-in ceremony was delayed after 
it was reported that the NPFL had made a last-minute change to 
its nominee on the council replacing Isaac Musa with Robert 
Brice. From Monrovia, Nianate Allison telexed this report. 
  Liberians today joyously sang national songs and shouted: 
The Lone Star forever, Lone Star forever, as the country moved 
closer to reunification with the induction into office of the 
five-man Transitional Council. The faces of many in the 
half-century-old Centennial Hall were brightened when Chief 
Justice James Bull administered the oath of office of the 
five-member council. The ceremony finally began after nearly 
five hours of delay. An official of the outgoing interim 
government said later the delay was to clear remaining hurdles. 
Council Chairman David Kpomakpor and Phillip Banks are nominees 
of the dissolved interim government of Amos Sawyer; while 
co-chairman, Isaac Musa, represents the NPFL. ULIMO is 
represented by Mohamed Sheriff and (Dexter Tayul). 
  ECOWAS [Economic Community of West African States] chairman, 
Benin's president Nicephore Soglo, who attended the ceremony, 
urged Liberians to unite and work rapidly to achieve the 
democratic institutions you have so long desired. He said: 
Everyone of you have much to forgive and to forget because that 
is the only way peace can come to Liberia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

