<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taylor Faction Reportedly Still `Uncooperative' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0703221394 Lagos NTA Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0703221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Lagos NTA Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Under the ECOWAS [Economic 
Community of West African States] peace agreement signed last 
July, the collective presidency comprising the NPFL [National 
Patriotic Front of Liberia], the outgoing interim government, 
and ULIMO [United Liberation Movement for Democracy in Liberia] 
is supposed to lead the country through democratic elections 
scheduled for 7 September this year. The inauguration of the new 
ruling body is also to coincide with the disarming of the 
various factions by the ECOWAS peace monitoring group, ECOMOG 
[ECOWAS Cease-Fire Monitoring Group]. Reports say ECOMOG has 
set up six sites around Monrovia where weapons will be 
collected. The United Nations is supervising the disarmament 
process but reports say that Mr. Taylor's faction is still 
uncooperative. 
  [Begin Taylor recording] We will fight and continue to fight 
anyone wanting to subvert the sovereignty of this nation by 
trying to take this land. They will have to fight me and 
everyone else after me if they intend to stay here forever. [end 
recording] 
  While the ECOMOG troops man checkpoints and ensure general 
security of life and property arms are still carried freely by 
members of the warring factions. Interim President Amos Sawyer 
is wary of this development. 
  [Begin Sawyer recording] We see that in Somalia; we see that 
elsewhere. Why are we immune from that kind of business, and why 
do we need anybody to go out there and stir this up? [end 
recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

