<H3> <TI>   ECOMOG Chief Warns of ULIMO Infighting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0703171394 Gbarnga Radio ELRL in English 1400 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0703171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Gbarnga Radio ELRL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The ECOMOG [Economic Community of West African 
States Cease-Fire Monitoring Group] high command has warned the 
leadership of ULIMO [United Liberation Movement for Democracy in 
Liberia] not to allow their infighting in Tubmanburg to spill 
over into Monrovia. ECOMOG field commander, Major General John 
Inienger, gave the warning yesterday when he summoned the 
dismissed leader of ULIMO, Alhaji Koromah, for consultations. A 
serious split developed within the ranks of ULIMO between Krahn 
elements loyal to ULIMO military chief, Roosevelt Johnson, and 
Mandingo elements of Alhaji Koromah following the failure of Dr. 
Mohamed Sheriff to obtain a position on the State Council. Dr. 
Sheriff was being supported by Alhaji Koromah, but lost the vice 
chairmanship of the council to Mr. Thomas Ziah of the same 
organization. Ziah is being supported by General Roosvelt 
Johnson and other Krahn elements within ULIMO. 
  Following news of Mr. Ziah's election over Dr. Sheriff, 
ULIMO 
leader Koromah has announced the sacking of Ziah and replaced 
him (?by Dr. Sheriff). The dismissal of Mr. Ziah who challenged 
[words indistinct] the military wing of ULIMO subsequently 
announced the dismissal of Alhaji Koromah. Gen. Roosevelt 
Johnson announced that he had taken over the leadership of 
ULIMO, disbanded the political wing [words indistinct]. Reports 
say the infighting in ULIMO has led to serious gun battle among 
its soldiers at the Po River in Tubmanburg ULIMO headquarters. 
The fighting was sparked off after Alhaji Koromah ordered the 
disarming of Krahn elements of ULIMO loyal to Johnson. Johnson 
forces are reported to have resisted the order, which resulted 
in a serious gun battle. Alhaji Koromah is said to be confused 
as the situation is now reported to be beyond his control. Of 
late, Koromah has been attempting to commercialize ULIMO [word 
indistinct] $5 million as compensation to cooperate with the 
peace process. 

</TEXT>

