<F P=101> Mali </F>
<H3> <TI>   Konare, France's Roussin Discuss CFA Devaluation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0403224294 Bamako Radiodiffusion-Television du Mali Radio 
in French 1500 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0403224294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bamako Radiodiffusion-Television du Mali Radio 
in French 1500 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Alpha Oumar Konare this morning received 
French Cooperation Minister Michel Roussin, who had already held 
a working session with Prime Minister Ibrahim Boubacar Keita and 
Finance Minister Soumaila Cisse. Discussions centered on 
France's cooperation to support the Malian Government's and 
people's efforts following the devaluation of the CFA franc. 
Here is Michel Roussin speaking to Mahamadou Kone. 
  [Begin Roussin recording] During this working session, we 
discussed how to organize our cooperation at this difficult time 
for us all -- for Malians and their brothers in other franc zone 
countries and also for us, the French. A number of pledges have 
been made and as Prime Minister Edouard Balladur stated and 
President Mitterrand reiterated in Yamoussoukro, France honors 
its commitments and France is here to support the substantial 
efforts made by the government and especially by the people, who 
understand that once this difficult period is over, it will be 
followed by economic growth and development will become a 
reality. For this reason, we must remain by the side of our 
African partners and this is what I have come to discuss in 
concrete terms with the prime minister and the finance minister. 
  My talks were less technical with the president than they 
were with the prime minister and the finance minister. The 
president gave a broad overview of the prevailing situation in 
the subregion. Of course, we also discussed how to manage the 
effects of the devaluation. I confirmed to the president 
France's friendly support for Mali during this delicate period, 
as my presence here today in Bamako with a large delegation 
attests. We also discussed the upcoming summit in Ouagadougou, 
where leaders of the members of the West African Economic and 
Monetary Union are scheduled to meet and together draw the first 
conclusions from the effects of the devaluation and get 
organized for the next phase of this courageous exercise which 
-- I am optimistic -- can enable everyone to experience an 
economic rebirth. [end recording] 
  Mahamadou Kone also informs us that the French cooperation 
minister will leave Bamako for Paris this afternoon. 

</TEXT>

